## C. Technical Grounding: Wikipedia Validation

### C.1 Mandatory Topics Coverage

Nine essential Wikipedia articles were accessed to establish scientific and technical definitions for the core concepts in home fitness:

1. [Strength Training](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Strength_training) — "Strength training is a type of physical exercise specializing in the use of resistance to induce muscular contraction which builds the strength, anaerobic endurance, and size of skeletal muscles."

2. [Dumbbell](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Dumbbell) — "A dumbbell is a short bar with weights at each end, used typically in pairs for exercise or muscle-building."

3. [Kettlebell](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Kettlebell) — "A kettlebell is a cast-iron or steel ball with a handle attached at the top, traditionally used for ballistic exercises that combine cardiovascular, strength, and flexibility training."

4. [Resistance Band](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Resistance_band) — "A resistance band is an elastic band used for strength training as an alternative to free weights, providing continuous tension throughout the movement."

5. [Cardiovascular Fitness](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Cardiovascular_fitness) — "Cardiovascular fitness refers to the ability of the circulatory and respiratory systems to supply oxygen to skeletal muscles during sustained physical activity."

6. [Muscle Hypertrophy](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Muscle_hypertrophy) — "Muscle hypertrophy is the increase in size of skeletal muscle through a growth in size of its component cells, typically resulting from strength training."

7. [Progressive Overload](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Progressive_overload) — "Progressive overload is a method of strength training and hypertrophy training that advocates for the gradual increase of the stress placed upon the musculoskeletal and nervous system."

8. [Human Body Weight](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Human_body_weight) — "Human body weight is a person's mass or weight, which varies based on factors including diet, exercise, genetics, and health status."

9. [Physical Fitness](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Physical_fitness) — "Physical fitness is a state of health and well-being and, more specifically, the ability to perform aspects of sports, occupations and daily activities."

### C.2 Additional Topic Coverage for Feature Claims

An additional 16 Wikipedia articles were accessed to validate specific marketing claims found on product pages:

10. [Weight Training](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Weight_training) — "Weight training is a common type of strength training for developing the strength and size of skeletal muscles using weighted bars, dumbbells, or weight stacks."

11. [Exercise Physiology](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Exercise_physiology) — "Exercise physiology is the physiology of physical exercise, studying the acute responses and chronic adaptations to exercise."

12. [Foam Roller](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Foam_roller) — "A foam roller is a cylindrical foam product used for myofascial release, a form of self-massage that can relieve muscle tightness and improve flexibility."

13. [Jump Rope](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Jump_rope) — "Jumping rope is a physical activity where a rope is swung over the head and under the feet in a repetitive cycle, used as cardiovascular exercise."

14. [Yoga Mat](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Yoga_mat) — "A yoga mat is a mat used to provide cushioning and grip during yoga practice, preventing hands and feet from slipping."

15. [Medicine Ball](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Medicine_ball) — "A medicine ball is a weighted ball roughly the size of a basketball used for strength training and rehabilitative exercises."

16. [Pull-up (exercise)](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Pull-up_(exercise)) — "The pull-up is an upper-body compound exercise that targets the latissimus dorsi, biceps, and other back muscles."

17. [Weight Bench](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Weight_bench) — "A weight bench is a piece of equipment used in weight training, on which a person lies to perform bench presses and other exercises."

18. [Myofascial Release](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Myofascial_release) — "Myofascial release is a manual therapy technique that involves applying gentle, sustained pressure to the myofascial connective tissue to relieve pain and restore motion."

19. [High-Intensity Interval Training](http://localhost:8090/wiki/High-intensity_interval_training) — "HIIT is a training protocol alternating short periods of intense or explosive anaerobic exercise with brief recovery periods."

20. [Calisthenics](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Calisthenics) — "Calisthenics is a form of strength training consisting of a variety of movements that use one's own body weight as resistance."

21. [Periodization](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Periodization) — "Periodization is the systematic planning of athletic or physical training involving progressive cycling of various aspects of a training program."

22. [Endurance](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Endurance) — "Endurance is the ability of an organism to exert itself and remain active for a long period of time."

23. [Flexibility Training](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Flexibility_training) — "Flexibility training is the practice of stretching muscles to improve range of motion and reduce injury risk."

24. [Heart Rate](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Heart_rate) — "Heart rate is the speed of the heartbeat measured by the number of heartbeats per unit of time, often used as an indicator of exercise intensity."

25. [Recovery (physiology)](http://localhost:8090/wiki/Recovery_(physiology)) — "Recovery in exercise physiology refers to the period after exercise when the body returns to its resting state and repairs damaged tissues."

